[1] Philippines (Western Visayas)
Date: Fri 17 Aug 2007
Source: GMA News TV [edited]
<http://www.gmanews.tv/story/56493/Dengue-cases-in-Western-Visayas-up-163>

The Department of Health (DOH) in Western Visayas has recommended the
activation of a local dengue task force following a 163 per cent
increase in dengue cases, including 29 deaths, [compared to 2006].
Iloilo-based online news site The News Today
<http://www.thenewstoday.info>
reported Friday [17 Aug 2007] afternoon that the Regional
Epidemiology and Surveillance Unit (RESU) recorded 2064 dengue cases
from 1 Jan - 4 Aug [2007].
Last year [2006], The RESU recorded only 776 cases of dengue for the
entire region, including 9 deaths.
Negros Occidental and Iloilo are the provinces with the highest
number of cases, at 507 and 508 respectively.
Dengue cases were clustered in the cities of Bacolod, Sagay and
Victorias, and in Hinoba-an town in Negros Occidental. In Iloilo,
they noted a clustering in Oton and Pavia towns.
The RESU considered Bacolod City, which had 595 dengue cases and 5
deaths, a hotspot because of the "increase in the number of cases for
2 consecutive weeks, even though the number is still within the
expected range."
Last year [2006], Bacolod City only had 205 cases, 3 of whom died.
Iloilo City had 341 cases and 6 deaths this year [2007] compared to
155 last year, with 4 deaths. Capiz has 38; Aklan, 35; Guimaras, 25;
and Antique, 15 cases.
The RESU report said dengue afflicted both the young and the old.
"Age of cases ranged from 2 months to 78 years with median age of 10
years," the report stated.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Joseph P. Dudley
[An interactive map of Western Visayas, showing its location in the
Philippines, can be accessed at:
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_Visayas>.
- Mod.TY]
