[2] Cambodia
Date: Wed 15 Aug 2007
Source: The Times of India [edited]
<http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/World/Rest_of_World/Dengue_toll_in_Cambodia_rises_above_300_this_year/articleshow/2283092.cms>

Dengue fever has killed at least 333 Cambodians this year [2007],
most of them children, and many more could die before the rainy
season ends next month [September 2007], senior health officials said
on Wednesday [17 Aug 2007]. The disease, which killed 116 Cambodians
in 2006, has spread across the impoverished nation and infected 31
136 people this year, most of them in the countryside where living
conditions are poor and children are vulnerable, they said.
More could die with the monsoon season, ideal breeding weather for
the mosquitoes which carry the disease and not due to fade until the
end of September 2007, he said.
A publicity campaign against the disease, including admonitions to
clean containers at home every 10 days to ensure mosquitoes cannot
breed in them, has borne little fruit.
The World Bank, the World Health Organization and the Red Cross have
provided pesticides to kill mosquitoes, and the Asian Development
Bank (ADB) gave USD 300 000.
Cambodia, whose health care system was devastated in 30 years of
civil war, spends about USD 3 per person on health a year, according
to the World Bank.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Joseph P. Dudley
[This report illustrates the serious challenge that community-based
dengue virus vector control programs present in poor countries.
Prudent use of larvacides, along with the elimination of _Aedes_
breeding sites, can provide effective reduction of dengue virus
transmission. Adulticides are likely to provide only temporary reduction.
A map of Cambodia can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/cambodia_pol_97.jpg>.
- Mod.TY]
