[3] Thailand
Date: Wed 15 Aug 2007
Source: Phuket Gazette [edited]
<http://www.phuketgazette.net/news/index.asp?fromsearch=yes&Id=5889>

A 9-year-old boy is suspected of becoming the latest victim of dengue
fever in Phuket. If the disease is confirmed, he will be the 3rd
person in Phuket killed by the disease this year [2007].
The boy lived in Koh Kaew and died at Vachira Phuket Hospital 4 Aug [2007].
The tests to determine whether dengue hemorrhagic fever was the cause
of death will take 2 weeks, officials at the hospital said.
Dr Wanchai Sattayawutthipong, chief of Phuket Provincial Health
Office (PPHO) told the Gazette that there has been an outbreak of
dengue fever in Thailand this year [2007]. "There have been 2
confirmed deaths by dengue fever in Phuket this year, and this latest
case is pending confirmation. The earlier cases were deaths of 2
adults, aged between 25 - 35," he said. "It shows that people in
every age group are vulnerable to the disease."
Last year [2006], there were no deaths associated with dengue,
although 136 people contracted the disease. So far this year [2007],
more than 200 people have contracted dengue.
Dr Wanchai said there are easy prevention methods that should reduce
the number of dengue cases.
"In the coming weeks, officers will go around Phuket and publicize
the dangers related to dengue fever. We will also teach people how to
protect themselves and their families from dengue.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Joseph P. Dudley
[As Dr. Wanchai indicated, the prevention methods as such are
relatively easy. Getting local people to put the methods into
rigorous practice is difficult.
Phuket is a major tourist stop in Thailand, and dengue cases may
discourage visitors from coming. It is located in southeast Thailand,
on the shores of the Straits of Malacca in the Andaman Sea. A map of
Thailand, showing the location of Phuket can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/thailand_admin_2005.jpg>.
- Mod.TY]
