[4] Malaysia
Date: Thu 16 Aug 2007
Source: Daily Express [edited]
<http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news.cfm?NewsID=52077>

Dengue fever cases in the country recorded a slight increase in the
32nd week of this year [2007].
A total of 1010 cases and 5 deaths were registered from 5 - 11 Aug
[2007] compared with 994 cases and 2 deaths the previous week, said
the Health Ministry's disease control director Datuk Dr Hassan Abdul
Rahman. He, however, said the situation was under control.
Dr Hassan said Kelantan recorded the highest increase of 9 per cent,
with 158 cases from 145 the previous week. This was followed by
Penang, which recorded 72 cases compared with 45 cases the previous
week and Sabah, with 35 cases compared with 55 cases the previous
week, he said in a statement here Wednesday [15 Aug 2007].
However, Selangor had recorded a drop, with 243 cases compared with
255 the previous week. The dengue situation is also improving in
Kuala Lumpur and Johor. Kuala Lumpur recorded 128 cases (143 cases
the previous week) and Johor 88 cases (119 cases).
Dr Hassan said 731 of 67 633 premises inspected between 5 - 11 Aug
[2007] were found to be breeding grounds for mosquitoes.
Of them, 78.5 per cent, or 574 premises, were houses, followed by
factories (10.2 per cent), land and unoccupied lots (9.2 per cent),
and playgrounds (6.3 per cent).
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Joseph P. Dudley
[An interactive map of Malaysia showing the administrative units
mentioned can be accessed at:
<http://encarta.msn.com/map_701513676/Kelang.html>.
- Mod.TY]
