[5] Bhutan
Date: Thu 18 Aug 2007
Source: Kuensel On Line [edited]
<http://www.kuenselonline.com/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=8911>

The Phuentsholing General Hospital has referred a patient diagnosed
with Dengue fever to the Thimphu National Referral Hospital.
A 68-year-old woman from Gatiya, Samtse was admitted to the
Phuentsholing hospital on 11 Aug 2007 with fever and pain in the
limbs. According to the District medical Officer, Dr. Kesang, she was
also suffering from kidney failure with upper gastrointestinal
bleeding. She was referred to Thimphu on 15 Aug [2007].
A 2nd patient, from lower Phuentsholing town, who was also diagnosed
with Dengue on 11 Aug [2007] has been discharged but is on medication.
Phuentsholing town, meanwhile, has been hit with viral fever. Around
500 people visited the Outpatient Department at Phuentsholing General
Hospital with complaints of fever, body ache and heat rash last week.
"It is because of the fluctuations in temperature and humidity
levels," said Dr. Kesang. "Different types of virus become active and
spread rapidly in such climatic conditions."
The metrology unit with the trade ministry recorded a maximum
humidity of 92 per cent on Tuesday [16 Aug 2007]. It was 84 per cent on Monday.
[Byline Passang Norbu]
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Joseph P. Dudley
[With the approximately 500 people reporting to the outpatient clinic
for fever, body ache and rash, one wonders whether some or all of
these patients might be dengue cases as well. ProMED would be
interested in knowing what laboratory tests were done to establish
the dengue fever diagnosis for the 2 patients mentioned above and
whether the fever patients were tested for dengue viruses or IgM antibody.
A map of Bhutan can be accessed at:
<http://www.lonelyplanet.com/mapshells/indian_subcontinent/bhutan/bhutan.htm>,
and a map showing the location of Phuentsholing can be accessed at:
<http://worldatlas.com/webimage/countrys/asia/lgcolor/btcolor.htm>.
The WHO (World Health Organization) description of dengue fever and
the more deadly dengue hemorrhagic fever [DHF] can be found in
ProMED-mail's "Dengue/DHF update 20070514.1541."
ProMED-mail thanks the contributors to this update and encourages
others to contribute reports also. - Mod.TY]
